## Go further

### A. Let TypeScript infer the type

```ts
const city = "Bowie";
```

TypeScript can often infer the type without you writing `: string`.

### B. Narrowing in conditionals

```ts
function printValue(value: string | number): void {
  if (typeof value === "string") {
    console.log(value.toUpperCase());
  } else {
    console.log(value.toFixed(2));
  }
}
```

This is one of the big TypeScript advantages: the type system narrows based on runtime checks. ([TypeScript][5])

### C. Prefer `const` unless you need reassignment

```ts
const siteName = "Lab Tracker";
let retryCount = 3;
```

That matches the handbook guidance around `const` and `let`. ([TypeScript][4])

